course: main course
time required: 40 minutes
---

Boil your #kettle{}. Cut the bottom root and the top dark green part off the @leek{1}. Cut in half lengthways then slice into half moon shapes (about ½cm wide). Cut the top and bottom off one of the @Braeburn apple{2}(one peeled, one sliced into rounds), slice into two rounds per person, then remove the middle with a sharp #knife{}. Peel the other apple, remove the core and then chop into small ½cm chunks. Put the @Tenderstem® broccoli{2} on a #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @olive oil{}, a @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{}. Leave to the side. Preheat your #oven{} to 200 degrees.

Dissolve the @chicken stock pot{1} in a #jug{} of boiling @water{450}.

Put a large #saucepan{} on medium heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{} and add your leek and chopped apple (leave your apple rounds for later). Cook for ~{5-7%minutes} until soft, then add the @couscous{225}, olive oil (amount specified in the ingredient list) and stock. Stir together. Once your couscous mixture has come to the boil, put a lid on the pan, take it off the heat and leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until everything else is ready.

Cut the @pork medallion{4} in half through the middle to make two medallions per person. Lay the @streaky bacon rasher{8} on a #board{} and place one pork medallion on top of each bacon rasher. Divide the @wholegrain mustard{2} between your medallions so you have a dollop on each, then lay an apple round on top of your mustard. Fold your bacon over your apple to form a parcel.

Put a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Once hot, add each pork parcel, apple-side down. Cook for ~{2-3%minutes} until golden brown, then turn over and cook on the other side for the same amount of time. Once done, pop them on a lined #baking tray{} on the top shelf of your oven for ~{7-10%minutes}.

> The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Pop your broccoli on the second shelf of your oven, at the same time as your pork parcels, for ~{7%minutes}.

While your pork parcels and broccoli are cooking, remove the @sage{½} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop them. Once your couscous is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir through your sage.

When everything is ready, serve your appley leek couscous on plates with your pork parcels on top and your broccoli on the side. Enjoy!